.\" Manual page for nvflux
.TH NVFLUX 1 "February 2026" "nvflux 1.1" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
nvflux \- manage NVIDIA GPU profiles (safe, limited nvidia-smi helper)
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B nvflux
[\fICOMMAND\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
nvflux is a small, minimal setuid-root helper that allows unprivileged users to run
a constrained subset of nvidia-smi operations to change GPU persistence, memory
clock and graphics clock behaviour. It is intended for desktop use so users can
switch GPU profiles without sudo.
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.B performance
Lock GPU memory and graphics clocks to the highest supported values.
.TP
.B balanced
Lock GPU memory and graphics clocks to mid-range supported values.
.TP
.B powersaver
Lock GPU memory and graphics clocks to the lowest supported values.
.TP
.B auto, reset
Reset all clock locks so the driver can manage clocks automatically.
.TP
.B status
Show last saved profile for the calling (real) user.
.TP
.B clock
Print current GPU memory and graphics clocks (MHz) as reported by nvidia-smi.
.TP
.B --restore
Reapply last saved profile for the calling user (reads ~/.local/state/nvflux/state).
.TP
.B -h, --help
Show help and exit.
.TP
.B -v, --version
Show version and exit.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Restore last saved profile on login:
.B exec --no-startup-id nvflux --restore
.TP
Switch to performance profile:
.B nvflux performance
.SH FILES
.TP
.B ~/.local/state/nvflux/state
Per-user saved profile (created/updated by nvflux).
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR nvidia-smi (1)
